Part 1

The park bench was made of iron slats painted green.

The paint had blistered from the Kolkata heat, peeling away in long, curved strips that looked like dried snake skins on the grass.

It sat in the middle of Bagbazar park, under a large banyan tree whose aerial roots had grown down to touch the ground, enclosing the bench on three sides like a wooden cage.

Vikram sat there in the mornings.

He had started sitting there after Sarita left for Delhi.

She had taken five patients with her, the ones who had recovered enough to help her set up the new shelter home near the Delhi airport.

"Rehman will handle Bagbazar," she had told Vikram before she boarded the train. "He has the ledger in his head, Vikram. He knows which distributor is late and which tap is leaking."

"I am here," Vikram had said.

"You are here physically," she said, leaning on her cane. "But your mind is still sweeping the dust. Let the boy do the numbers. He likes them."

He did.

---

Rehman brought the register to the park bench at eleven.

He sat on the iron slats beside Vikram, his blue canvas bag kept between his feet.

He was twenty-two now.

His shoulders had gone wider, his jaw carrying the sharp, dry line of an adult who spent more time talking to bank managers than to patients.

He wore a clean, white khadi kurta, but his shoes were still the same cheap canvas, now grey with Kolkata mud.

"The donations are not enough, uncle," Rehman said.

"They are enough for the dal," Vikram said.

"But not for the medicine. The government supply is late. The local supplier wants twelve percent interest on the credit. I told him he is a thief. He said the bank doesn't accept moral arguments."

He closed the register.

The green cloth cover had gone dark near the edges from where his palms had rested.

"We need a brand," Rehman said.

"A brand is for businesses, Rehman."

"If we have to beg for every rupee of medicine, we are not helping, uncle. We are just waiting for rich men to feel guilty on their birthdays and write cheques."

"What would you do?"

"Make our own things," Rehman said, his voice rising slightly. "The patients here have hands. They can pack medical kits. They can make incense from the temple flowers Ramu's nephew brings. Simple things."

He leaned forward, his elbows on his knees, looking at Vikram.

"Greed is bad, uncle. My mother taught me that. But *need* is not bad. If we have to buy paracetamol, we need money. If we have to fight the municipal clerks, we need power. Why should the devils have all the money and do what they want, while we stay small and sweep the dust?"

Vikram looked at the banyan roots.

A row of red ants was moving along a split in the bark, carrying a single grain of sugar.

"Power is a heavy thing, Rehman," Vikram said.

"It is only heavy when you carry it alone," the boy said. "We will carry it together. The patients will make the incense. I will sell it to the distributors."

He stood up.

"I have already decided the name."

"What name?"

"Ummed," Rehman said. "It means hope."

Vikram's hand stopped on the iron slat of the bench.

*Ummed.*

The name had the soft, Urdu sound of a letter written on ruled paper from Cuttack.

*He changed my name to Ummed.*

He looked at Rehman.

The boy was looking at the banyan leaves, his face clear, his smile open and free of the Odisha dust.

"It is my mother's name," Rehman said. "She told me once that when everything is lost, only Ummed remains."

"It is a Muslim name," Vikram said.

"She converted," the boy said, without looking back. "But the meaning didn't change."

He picked up his canvas bag.

"I will print the first labels today. Simple yellow paper. Like the envelope my mother sent."

He walked away down the gravel path of the park.

Vikram sat on the bench.

The green paint felt hot under his fingers, but the name *Ummed* was still sitting on the grass between the banyan roots.

Unmoving.

Growing.

[End of Part 1]
